제가 직접 만들어서 사용중인 #스트라이몬 딜레이/리버브 프리셋입니다
#예배사운드 에서 너무나도 중요한 #공간감을 만들기위해 
엠비언트 사운드만 10년을넘게 연구하고 실전에서 예배하며 여기까지 왔습니다
#타임라인 : (총3개) / #빅스카이 : (총3개)
1.DUAL delay : 2개의 딜레이(점8, 4분음표)가 함께 썩인 딜레이 사운드로 스테레오 출력시 입체적인 사운드를 연출할수 있습니다 
2. ice delay : 옥타브를 이용한 환상적인 딜레이 사운드 입니다 기타로 Pad사운드 연출시 Madaway 리버브 와 함께 섞어 사용하시면 천국의 사운드를 느끼실수 있을것입니다 ^^
3. ice delay 2 : 코드 연주나 아르페지오 연주시에 사용하시면 좋습니다
빅스카이 : (총3개)
1. Bloom : 깊고 넓은 Pad사운드 리버브이며 엄지 손가락으로 부드럽게  스트로크 하시며 사용하시면 됩니다 
2.  chorale 1 : 여러사람들의 목소리 효과이며 천사들의 합창과도 같은 리버브 사운드입니다 
3. chorale 2(wider) : 더 넓은 chorale 리버브 사운드로 pad사운드 연출시에 아주 환상적인 pad사운드를 표현할수 있습니다

Today’s offering in my series of arrangements of traditional Irish tunes leading up to St. Patty’s Day is “Old Tipperary.” I’ve never seen this one transcribed for guitar before and Gsus4 tuning, DGDGCD, is absolutely perfect to facilitate performing this lively jig. I was drawn to this one by the name, as there was an Irish pub in Dallas called “Tipperary Inn” that I would visit to drink Irish draughts, whiskey, and listen to local Celtic music musicians. I kept this one pretty simple so that the quick tempo is possible, but I have a more challenging version with stylistic trills and bass that has a contrary movement. #oldtipperary #jig #arrangement #irishguitar #celticmusic #opentuning #alteredtuning #alternatetuning #gsus4 #guitarmusic #irishmusic #irishjig #trad #irishtrad #sheetmusic #guitarlesson #guitarlessons #pbnmusiclessons #tipperaryinn #ireland

Acorde "Gsus4" 🎹
Saludos, aclarando acordes en el #piano El acorde #gsus4 se trata de una triada!, NO de una tétrada. Estamos hablando de SOLO 3 notas. Fundamental, Cuarta Justa y Quinta Justa. (Solo esas 3). En este caso de "G" o "Sol Mayor" serían G (Fundamental), C (Cuarta Justa), D (Quinta Justa). No sería una extensión sino una triada. 
En el caso de las inversiones se colocará una barra (/) que dirá el bajo (en mano izquierda.)
Primera Inversión Gsus4/C 
Do-Re-Sol (Bajo en Do)
Segunda Inversión Gsus4/D
Re-Sol-Do (Bajo en Re)
Para el resto de los demás tonos (12 en música occidental) tomar en cuenta esta regla. (1-4-5). 🎹
Apoyo de webside: 
https://www.acordespiano.com/gsus4/

Just had a chat with @victorwooten Victor Wooten and he told us how great the name Gsus4 is...
.
"Gsus4 always leads to the One(G Major) by raising the third. Just like Jesus is leading us to the One and was raised on the third.
.
Gsus4 is not dominant, its suspended. Just like Jesus was. He was suspended and came to serve, not to be served.
.
Gsus4 has its own spiritual but also powerful meaning behind it. You guys have picked an awesome name for your shop."

Seit 25 Jahren gibt es das Sinnflut-Kultur-Festival in meiner Heimatstadt Erding. 1993 durfte ich mit meiner damaligen Band "Gsus4" bei der ersten Sinnflut-Premiere dabei sein. Damals bestand die Bühne noch größtenteils aus einem umfunktionierten LKW-Anhänger. Der Platz war kleiner. Alles war etwas improvisierter und die Erdinger konnten mit diesem neuen alternativen Festival auf dem Erdinger Volksfestplatz noch nicht so richtig viel anfangen. Aber die Macher Peter Feller und Börnie Sparakowski ließen sich nicht beirren und machten trotz erheblicher Startschwierigkeiten weiter. Heute ist das Festival aus Erding nicht mehr wegzudenken. Am Donnerstag gehts wieder los! Ich freu mich drauf ..... auch nach 25 Jahren! Vielen Dank!

P.S.: Das Foto wurde nicht auf "alt" getrimmt. Mein Bruder Franz-Xaver Bauer hatte damals tatsächlich einen schwarz-weiß-Film im Fotoapparat.

I came up with the term ‘Bell Harmonics’ for my two handed harmonic technique after writing the song ‘Pepperleaf Pipes’. Originally the piece was going to be called ‘Pepperbell Pipes’ and so I was going to name my technique ‘Pepperbell Harmonics’ but decided to shorten it to simply ‘Bell Harmonics’. I had been developing this technique and my love for harmonics since a child but it was Guitar World featuring me twice for this technique and then my song ‘Bell’s Harmonic’ which started to bring notoriety. Thanks for everyone’s support on this journey! Here’s a quick excerpt from my 100,000 harmonics a week exercise using the @soundbrenner metronome.

@ecodetrave got me thinking about the opening 'mystery chord" from The Beatles song Hard Days Night. This recording is based on the page from The Beatles Complete Scores book about one post back. Since I only have two hands instead of six, I used my trusty @tcelectronic #ditto pedal to layer these sounds. The click is me counting in so I could play each part at the right time. The Ditto will let you layer as many sounds as you want. If you notice on the score, guitar 2 is a twelve string. I don't have one, so I played the chord once as written then an octave higher to emulate the 12. There's also a low D in the bass which I used a drop D tuning for. I think I got fairly close, but I'm sure the Beatles had a little going on than just this. Anyway, just a fun experiment. If you are not familiar with this song...you should be!!  Also if you compare this pitch with the Beatles original recording you'll hear they are different. I'm pretty sure the speed on the original was sped up making a slightly sharper pitch. I'm tuned standard here. 😜😎🎸 #thebeatles #harddaysnight #johnlennon #paulmccartney #georgeharrison #ringostarr #Gsus4 #dwguitarvids #tcelectronic #ditto #looper #dittolooper #dittolooperpedal

TOP: Last week I'm teaching Riley (sweet, funny 13 y/o) a new way to play a G chord so she can add in the sus4 with her 1st finger for "Dead Flowers", a Stones she wanted to learn. She's really struggling with it and getting frustrated. I'm checking her finger placement and notice her "finger placement". "Uh, Riley. You tryin' to tell me somethin'?" She laughs and  swears it's accidental! Okay, I believe her.

BOTTOM: She comes is yesterday. "How you doing with the changes for "Dead Flowers", I ask. "I still can't get that G sup chord", she says. "Gsus4, and what did I tell you about using that word here. Hard, challenging, but none of that 'can't' crap!" She corrects herself, "it's really hard." Alright, let me see how ur doin' with it. (typical teen whining and griping follows). I look down and see the same "finger placement." Only now the nail is painted red. And it's the ONLY nail on that hand with polish! 
I confess that fingering that chord can make your "finger" do that, but you tell me -- accidental, or not?
